{
  "text": "; \u03d5 1 states that the perturbation of x A is absorbed within T p units of time, stabilising back to a value x A < h \u2032 for additional T d time units. Furthermore, within distance [w m , w M ] from the original perturbation, where w M is chosen such that we are within the spot of the non-perturbed system, \u03d5 2 \u2236= G [0,T ] (x A < h \u2032 ) is satisfied; i.e. no relevant effect is observed, the value of x A stably remains below h \u2032 . The meaning of \u03d5 pert is that the induced perturbation remains confined inside the original spot. In Fig. 3 (b) we report the evaluation of the quantitative semantics for \u03d5 pert , zooming in on the 15\u00d715 lower left corner of the original grid. All the locations that are not plotted have been evaluated and do not satisfy the property. As shown in the figure, the only location that satisfies this property is the perturbed one, [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] .",
